\left[\left({\frac {25\,mi}{100\,ft_{nat.gas}^{3}}}\right)\cdot \left({\fra=
c {100\,ft_{nat.gas}^{3}}{0.823\,gal_{nat.gas}}}\right)\right]=3D203\,mpg_{=
equiv}}"></span>
</p><p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Energy_Policy_Act_of_19=
92" title=3D"Energy Policy Act of 1992">Energy Policy Act of 1992</a> expan=
ded the definition of alternative fuel to include <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Liquefied_petroleum_gas" title=3D"Liquefied petroleum gas">=
liquefied petroleum gas</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hydro=
gen_vehicle" title=3D"Hydrogen vehicle">hydrogen</a>, liquid fuels derived =
from coal and biological materials, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Electric_vehicle" title=3D"Electric vehicle">electricity</a> and any othe=
r fuel that the Secretary of Transportation determines to be substantially =
non-petroleum based and has environmental and energy security benefits. Beg=
inning in 1993, manufacturers of these other alternative fuel automobiles t=
hat meet the qualifying requirements can also benefit for special treatment=
 in the calculation of their CAFE.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-NHTS2_17-1" class=3D"=
reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Miles_per_gallon_gasoli=
ne_equivalent#cite_note-NHTS2-17"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>17<s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"1994:_Gasoline_gallon_equiv=
alent">1994: Gasoline gallon equivalent</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection">=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/w/index.php?title=3DMiles_per_gallon_gasoline_equivalent&amp;action=
=3Dedit&amp;section=3D3" title=3D"Edit section: 1994: Gasoline gallon equiv=
alent"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span>=
</span></div>
<p>In 1994 the U.S. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/National_Insti=
tute_of_Standards_and_Technology" title=3D"National Institute of Standards =
and Technology">National Institute of Standards and Technology</a> (NIST) i=
ntroduced <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gasoline_gallon_equivale=
nt" title=3D"Gasoline gallon equivalent">gasoline gallon equivalent</a> (GG=
E) as a metric for fuel economy for <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Natural_gas_vehicle" title=3D"Natural gas vehicle">natural gas vehicles</=
a>. NIST defined a gasoline gallon equivalent (GGE) as 5.660 pounds of natu=
ral gas, and gasoline liter equivalent (GLE) as 0.678 kilograms of natural =
gas.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-18" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Miles_per_gallon_gasoline_equivalent#cite_note-18"><span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>18<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
>
</p>
