nroney label</a> for electric cars showing in prominent larger font the <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fuel_economy_in_automobiles" title=3D=
"Fuel economy in automobiles">fuel economy</a> rating in miles per <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/USgallon" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"=
USgallon">USgallon</a> gasoline equivalent for the 2011 <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nissan_Leaf" title=3D"Nissan Leaf">Nissan Leaf</a>. T=
he rating in kWh/100 miles is shown below MPG-e in smaller font.</div></div=
></div></div></div>
<p>As required by the 2007 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Energy_=
Independence_and_Security_Act" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Energy Indepe=
ndence and Security Act">Energy Independence and Security Act</a> (EISA), w=
ith the introduction of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Advanced-t=
echnology_vehicle" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Advanced-technology vehic=
le">advanced-technology vehicles</a> in the U.S. new information should be =
incorporated in the Monroney label of new cars and light-duty trucks sold i=
n the country, such as ratings on fuel economy, <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Greenhouse_gas_emissions" title=3D"Greenhouse gas emissions">=
greenhouse gas emissions</a>, and other <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Air_pollutant" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Air pollutant">air poll=
utants</a>. The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/U.S._Environmental=
_Protection_Agency" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"U.S. Environmental Prote=
ction Agency">U.S. Environmental Protection Agency</a> (EPA) and the <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/National_Highway_Traffic_Safety_Administ=
ration" title=3D"National Highway Traffic Safety Administration">National H=
ighway Traffic Safety Administration</a> (NHTSA) have conducted a series of=
 studies to determine the best way to redesign this label to provide consum=
ers with simple energy and environmental comparisons across all vehicles ty=
pes, including <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Battery_electric_ve=
hicle" title=3D"Battery electric vehicle">battery electric vehicles</a> (BE=
V), <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Plug-in_hybrid_electric_vehicl=
e" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Plug-in hybrid electric vehicle">plug-in =
hybrid electric vehicles</a> (PHEV), and conventional <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internal_combustion_engine" title=3D"Internal combustio=
n engine">internal combustion engine</a> vehicles powered by gasoline and d=
iesel, in order to help consumers choose more efficient and environmentally=
 friendly vehicles. These changes were proposed to be introduced in new veh=
icles beginning with model year 2012.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-EPAfueleconomy_3-3=
" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Miles_per_ga=
llon_gasoline_equivalent#cite_note-EPAfueleconomy-3"><span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"c=
ite_ref-EPAstudy10_31-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Miles_per_gallon_gasoline_equivalent#cite_note-EPAstudy10-31"><s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>30<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span><=
/a></sup>
</p><p>The EPA rating for on board energy efficiency for electric vehicles =
before 2010 was expressed as kilowatt hour per 100 miles (kWh/100&nbsp;mi).=
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-EVN2009_28-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Miles_per_gallon_gasoline_equivalent#cite_note-EVN2009-=
28"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>27<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-MiniE_32-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Miles_per_gallon_gasoline_equivalent#cite=
_note-MiniE-32"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>31<span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">]</span></a></sup> For example, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Window_sticker" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Window sticker">w=
indow sticker</a> of the 2009 Mini E showed an energy consumption of 33&nbs=
p;kWh/100&nbsp;mi for city driving and 36&nbsp;kWh/100&nbsp;mi on the highw=
ay, technically equivalent to 100&nbsp;mpg=E2=80=91e city and 94&nbsp;mpg=
=E2=80=91e highway.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-MiniE_32-1" class=3D"reference"><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Miles_per_gallon_gasoline_equivalent#c=
ite_note-MiniE-32"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>31<span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Similarly, the 2009 <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Tesla_Roadster_(2008)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Tesl=
a Roadster (2008)">Tesla Roadster</a> was rated 32&nbsp;kWh/100&nbsp;mi (11=
0&nbsp;mpg=E2=80=91e) in city and 33&nbsp;kWh/100&nbsp;mi (100&nbsp;mpg=E2=
=80=91e) on the highway.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-33" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Miles_per_gallon_gasoline_equivalent#cite=
_note-33"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>32<span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-34" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Miles_per_gallon_gasoline_equivalent#cite_no=
te-34"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>33<span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>As part of the research and redesign process, EPA conducted <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Focus_group" title=3D"Focus group">focus =
groups</a> where participants were presented with several options to expres=
s the consumption of electricity for <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Plug-in_electric_vehicle" title=3D"Plug-in electric vehicle">plug-in ele=
ctric vehicles</a>. The research showed that participants did not understan=
d the concept of a kilowatt hour as a measure of electric energy use despit=
e the use of this unit in their monthly electric bills. Instead, participan=
ts favored a miles per gallon equivalent, MPGe, as the metric to compare wi=
th the familiar miles per gallon used for gasoline vehicles. The research a=
lso concluded that the kWh per 100 miles metric was more confusing to focus=
 group participants compared to a miles per kWh. Based on these results, EP=
A decided to use the following fuel economy and fuel consumption metrics on=
 the redesigned labels: MPG (city and highway, and combined); MPGe (city an=
d highway, and combined); Gallons per 100 miles; kWh per 100 miles.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-EPAstudy10_31-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Miles_per_gallon_gasoline_equivalent#cite_note-EPAstudy10-3=
1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>30<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</s=
pan></a></sup>
</p><p>The proposed design and final content for two options of the new sti=
cker label that would be introduced in 2013 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Model_year" title=3D"Model year">model year</a> cars and trucks w=
ere consulted for 60 days with the public in 2010, and both include miles p=
er gallon equivalent and kWh per 100 miles as the fuel economy metrics for =
plug-in cars, but in one option MPGe and annual electricity cost are the tw=
o most prominent metrics.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-35" class=3D"reference"><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Miles_per_gallon_gasoline_equivalent#cit=
e_note-35"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>34<span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-36" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Miles_per_gallon_gasoline_equivalent#cite=
_note-36"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>35<span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">]</span></a></sup> In November 2010, EPA introduced MPGe as comparison m=
etric on its new sticker for fuel economy for the Nissan Leaf and the Chevr=
olet Volt.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-NYTEPA_9-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Miles_per_gallon_gasoline_equivalent#cite_note-=
NYTEPA-9"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>9<span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-USAT1124_10-1" class=3D"reference">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Miles_per_gallon_gasoline_equivale=
nt#cite_note-USAT1124-10"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>10<span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Hydrogen_56mpge_500px.jpg" class=3D"mw-file-d=
escription"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thum=
b/1/1d/Hydrogen_56mpge_500px.jpg/250px-Hydrogen_56mpge_500px.jpg" decoding=
=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"161" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file=
-width=3D"500" data-file-height=3D"322"></a><figcaption>Typical label for <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fuel_cell_vehicle" title=3D"Fuel ce=
ll vehicle">hydrogen fuel cell vehicles</a> expressed in MPGe, mandatory st=
arting with 2013 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Model_year" title=
=3D"Model year">model year</a></figcaption></figure>
<p>In May 2011, the NHTSA and EPA issued a joint final rule establishing ne=
w requirements for a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fuel_economy_=
and_environment_label" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Fuel economy and envi=
ronment label">fuel economy and environment label</a> that is mandatory for=
 all new passenger cars and trucks starting with model year 2013. The rulin=
g includes new labels for <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alternat=
ive_fuel" title=3D"Alternative fuel">alternative fuel</a> and <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alternative_propulsion" class=3D"mw-redirect" t=
itle=3D"Alternative propulsion">alternative propulsion</a> vehicles availab=
le in the US market, such as plug-in hybrids, electric vehicles, flexible-f=
uel vehicles, hydrogen fuel cell vehicle, and natural gas vehicles.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-EPA2013_11-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Miles_per_gallon_gasoline_equivalent#cite_note-EPA2013-11"><sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>11<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></=
a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-GCC2013_12-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Miles_per_gallon_gasoline_equivalent#cite_note-=
GCC2013-12"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>12<span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">]</span></a></sup> The common fuel economy metric adopted to allow the=
 comparison of alternative fuel and advanced technology vehicles with conve=
ntional internal combustion engine vehicles is <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Miles_per_gallon_of_gasoline_equivalent" class=3D"mw-redirect"=
 title=3D"Miles per gallon of gasoline equivalent">miles per gallon of gaso=
line equivalent</a> (MPGe). A gallon of gasoline equivalent means the numbe=
r of kilowatt hours of electricity, cubic feet of compressed natural gas (C=
NG), or kilograms of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hydrogen" tit=
le=3D"Hydrogen">hydrogen</a> that is equal to the energy in a gallon of gas=
oline.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-EPA2013_11-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Miles_per_gallon_gasoline_equivalent#cite_note-EP=
A2013-11"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>11<span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The new labels also show for the first time an estimate of how much =
fuel or electricity it takes to drive 100 miles (160&nbsp;km), introducing =
to U.S. consumers with fuel consumption per distance traveled, a metric com=
monly used in other countries. EPA explained that the objective is to avoid=
 the traditional miles per gallon metric that can be potentially misleading=
 when consumers compare fuel economy improvements, and known as the "MPG il=
lusion".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-EPA2013_11-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Miles_per_gallon_gasoline_equivalent#cite_note-=
EPA2013-11"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>11<span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>As mentioned above, confusion and misinterpretation is common in the=
 public between the two types of "<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Fuel_efficiency" title=3D"Fuel efficiency">fuel efficiency</a>". <b>Fuel ec=
onomy</b> measures how far a vehicle will go per amount of fuel (units of M=
PGe). <b>Fuel consumption</b> is the reciprocal of fuel economy, and measur=
es the fuel used to drive a fixed distance (units of gal/100 miles or kWh/1=
00 miles).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-37" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Miles_per_gallon_gasoline_equivalent#cite_note-37"><spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>36<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup> The unit of Gal/100 miles is accurately described as fuel consumpti=
on in some EPA brochures, but this unit appears in the fuel economy section=
 of the Monroney label (which does not use the term fuel consumption).<sup =
id=3D"cite_ref-38" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Miles_per_gallon_gasoline_equivalent#cite_note-38"><span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">[</span>37<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-39" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Miles_per_gallon_gasoline_equivalent#cite_note-39"><span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">[</span>38<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div style=3D"clear:both;" class=3D""></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Description">Description</h=
2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</=
span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DMiles_per_gall=
on_gasoline_equivalent&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D7" title=3D"Edit sec=
tion: Description"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-brack=
et">]</span></span></div>
<p>The miles per gallon gasoline equivalent is based on the energy content =
of gasoline. The energy obtainable from burning one US gallon of gasoline i=
s 115,000&nbsp;BTU, 33.70&nbsp;kWh, or 121.3&nbsp;MJ.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-mp=
ge_8-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Miles_=
per_gallon_gasoline_equivalent#cite_note-mpge-8"><span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">[</span>8<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>To convert the mile per gallon rating into other units of distance p=
er unit energy used, the mile per gallon value can be multiplied by one of =
the following factors to obtain other units:
</p>
<dl><dd><table>

<tbody><tr>
<td>1 MPGe</td>
<td>=E2=89=88 1&nbsp;mi/(33.70&nbsp;<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Kilowatt_hour" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Kilowatt hour">kW=C2=B7h</a=
>)
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td></td>
<td>=E2=89=88 8.696 &nbsp;mi/(million&nbsp;<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/BTU" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"BTU">BTU</a>)
</td></tr>
<tr>
