<p>The energy content of a particular fuel can vary somewhat given its spec=
ific chemistry and production method. For example, in the new efficiency ra=
tings that have been developed by the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/United_States_Environmental_Protection_Agency" title=3D"United States E=
nvironmental Protection Agency">United States Environmental Protection Agen=
cy</a> (EPA) for <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Battery_electric_=
vehicle" title=3D"Battery electric vehicle">battery electric vehicles</a> (=
BEVs) and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Plug-in_hybrid_electric_=
vehicle" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Plug-in hybrid electric vehicle">pl=
ug-in hybrid electric vehicles</a> (PHEVs) =E2=80=93 see below =E2=80=93 th=
e energy content of a gallon of gasoline is assumed to be 114,989.12 BTU or=
 33.7 kWh.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-mpge_8-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Miles_per_gallon_gasoline_equivalent#cite_note-mp=
ge-8"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>8<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]<=
/span></a></sup>
</p>
