<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Conversion_using_GGE">Conve=
rsion using GGE</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editse=
ction-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?titl=
e=3DMiles_per_gallon_gasoline_equivalent&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D16=
" title=3D"Edit section: Conversion using GGE"><span>edit</span></a><span c=
lass=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">Main article=
: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gasoline_gallon_equivalent" titl=
e=3D"Gasoline gallon equivalent">Gasoline gallon equivalent</a></div>
<p>The same method can be applied to any other alternative fuel vehicle whe=
n that vehicle's energy consumption is known. Generally the energy consumpt=
ion of the vehicle is expressed in units other than W=C2=B7h/mile, or Btu/m=
ile so additional arithmetic is required to convert to a gasoline gallon eq=
uivalent (GGE), using 33.7 kWh / gallon =3D 114989.17 btu / gallon.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-mpge_8-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Miles_per_gallon_gasoline_equivalent#cite_note-mpge-8"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>8<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Hydrogen_example_with_GGE">=
Hydrogen example with GGE</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D=
"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/inde=
x.php?title=3DMiles_per_gallon_gasoline_equivalent&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;se=
ction=3D17" title=3D"Edit section: Hydrogen example with GGE"><span>edit</s=
pan></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The 2008 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Honda_FCX_Clarity" cla=
ss=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Honda FCX Clarity">Honda FCX Clarity</a> is adv=
ertised to have a vehicle consumption of 72&nbsp;mi/kg-<span class=3D"chemf=
 nowrap">H<span class=3D"nowrap"><span style=3D"display:inline-block;margin=
-bottom:-0.3em;vertical-align:-0.4em;line-height:1em;font-size:80%;text-ali=
gn:left"><sup style=3D"font-size:inherit;line-height:inherit;vertical-align=
:baseline"></sup><br><sub style=3D"font-size:inherit;line-height:inherit;ve=
rtical-align:baseline">2</sub></span></span></span>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-hon=
da_88-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Miles=
_per_gallon_gasoline_equivalent#cite_note-honda-88"><span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">[</span>87<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Hydrogen at=
 atmospheric pressure has an energy density of 120 <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Joule" title=3D"Joule">MJ</a>/kg (113,738 BTU/kg),<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-eere_89-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Miles_per_gallon_gasoline_equivalent#cite_note-eere-89"><span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>88<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></su=
p> by converting this energy density to a GGE, it is found that 1.011&nbsp;=
kg of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hydrogen" title=3D"Hydrogen"=
>hydrogen</a> is needed to meet the equivalent energy of one gallon of gaso=
line. This conversion factor can now be used to calculate the MPGe for this=
 vehicle.
</p>
